Solution: Refactoring

Philipp Walter
on May 9

Hi Arjan,
great challenge and I didn't solved it by far not that elegant :-D

But I struggled with the external specification of the conditions-parameter with:
- multiple flags describing the same condition
- having the possitibility to select multiple conditions

Watching your solution the last functionality is not available anymore :-(

So I quickly refactored your refactored solution to:

def construct_parser(texts: dict[str, Any]) -> argparse.ArgumentParser:
parser = argparse.ArgumentParser(description=texts["cli_description"])
parser.add_argument("city", help=texts["help_city"])
parser.add_argument(
"-c",
"--condition",
dest="condition",
metavar="CONDITION",
default="temperature",
nargs="+",
choices=texts["conditions_all"]
+ texts["conditions_temperature"]
+ texts["conditions_humidity"]
+ texts["conditions_wind"],
help=texts["help_condition"],
)

parser.add_argument(
"--api-key",
default="123456789",
help=texts["help_api_key"],
)

return parser

def check_if_value_exists(list1: list[str], list2: list[str]) -> bool:
return any(value in list2 for value in list1)

def fetch_conditions_from_args(
arg_condition: list[str], texts: dict[str, Any]
) -> list[Condition]:

if check_if_value_exists(arg_condition, texts["conditions_all"]):
return [condition for condition in Condition]

conditions: list[Condition] = []
if check_if_value_exists(arg_condition, texts["conditions_humidity"]):
conditions.append(Condition.HUMIDITY)
if check_if_value_exists(arg_condition, texts["conditions_wind"]):
conditions.append(Condition.WIND)
if check_if_value_exists(arg_condition, texts["conditions_temperature"]):
conditions.append(Condition.TEMPERATURE)

return conditions

Sylvain Payot
on Jan 31

great challenge!
i was tempted to move away from the --conditions argument taking a list of values (including potentially invalid ones) and adopt a more classic set of boolean flags (e.g."-t", "--temperature" ). this presents the advantage that you can use the dest parameter in add_argument to map all those language-dependent boolean flags to the same condition argument so that the rest of your code remains language-independant... something like: 


for condition in ["temperature", "wind", "humidity", "all"]:

        parser.add_argument(

            *texts["flag_names"][condition],

            dest=condition,

            action="store_true",

            help=texts["help"][condition],

        )

that saves you the need for the fetch_conditions_from_args to map to the StrEnum...
on the other end, it loses flexibility in allowing users to control the order in which the weather conditions is printed... which i decided i could live with :)

Eduardo Motta de Moraes
on Sep 8, 2023

Interesting challenge.

I opted to abstract the entire parse configuration in a json file, that is then called like in the example below (config is a dict created from the json file).


def create_parser(config: dict[str, Any]) -> argparse.ArgumentParser:

    parser = argparse.ArgumentParser(description=config["description"])



    for argument in config["arguments"]:

        parser.add_argument(*argument["names"], **argument["attributes"])



    return parser
